Patient: How much water should I be drinking each day?

Healthcare Educator: About 6 to 9 cups daily, but it may vary based on your condition and body size.

Patient: Why should I limit my water intake?

Healthcare Educator: Too much fluid can make your heart work harder, worsening your heart failure symptoms.

Patient: Can I drink other fluids apart from water?

Healthcare Educator: Yes, but remember all fluids count towards your daily limit, including tea, coffee and soup.

Patient: How about alcohol? Can I drink that?

Healthcare Educator: It's best to avoid alcohol as it can weaken your heart muscle and exacerbate your heart failure. 

Patient: What about when it's really hot or I'm exercising?

Healthcare Educator: You may need extra fluid. But too much can strain your heart. Listen to your body's needs.

Patient: How will I know if I'm drinking too much fluid?

Healthcare Educator: You may notice weight gain, swelling in your legs or shortness of breath. Monitor your weight daily.

Patient: Is there a better time of day to drink fluids?

Healthcare Educator: Spread out your fluids throughout the day. Try not to drink a lot in a short time.

Patient: What if I get thirsty?

Healthcare Educator: Try rinsing your mouth or chewing gum. If you're still thirsty, have a small drink.

Patient: Are there any foods I should avoid?

Healthcare Educator: Yes, avoid high sodium foods, they make you thirsty and cause your body to retain fluid.